ameMeanings":[{"name":"d'Everard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Everett  .","French (northern), Walloon, and Dutch: variant of French and Walloon   Evrard  , Dutch   Everhard  .","Americanized form of German   Eberhardt   or   Everhardt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Everett","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal names <i>Everard</i> and <i>Everet</i>. These might occasionally be from the Old English form of the name, <i>Eoforheard</i> (from <i>eofor</i> ‘boar’ + <i>heard</i> ‘hardy, brave’), but many bearers of this name were undoubtedly Normans, who took it from the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Eburhard</i>, <i>Everhard</i>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret d'Everard was born from 1160 to 1165, in France. She had at least 1 son with Raynulph d'Arundel. She died in 1182, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Bet. 1160–1165–1182":"1160 kuni 1165–1182","1160–1241":"1160–1241","1180–1280":"1180–1280","1160–1182":"1160–1182","about 1180":"umbes 1180","Bet. 1160–1165":"1160 kuni 1165","1241":"1241","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1280":"1280","1180":"1180","Prideaux Trenarren, France":"Prantsusmaa","Trelow, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"Bet. 1160–1165–1182":"vuodesta 1160 vuoteen 1165–1182","1160–1241":"1160–1241","1180–1280":"1180–1280","1160–1182":"1160–1182","about 1180":"noin 1180","Bet. 1160–1165":"vuodesta 1160 vuoteen 1165","1241":"1241","1182":"1182","1160":"1160","1280":"1280","1180":"1180","Prideaux Trenarren, France":"Ranska","